  "nid": "1_2470",
  "title": "Upper limb injuries: Lunate and perilunate dislocation",
  "body_html": "<b>Mechanism of injury</b><br /><ul><li>High energy injury </li><li>Forceful loading of dorsiflexed/extended wrist. </li><li>Uncommon injury</li><li>Potential poor outcomes</li></ul><br /><b>Lunate and perilunate dislocation</b><br /><ul><li>In lunate dislocation the lunate displaces volarly into carpal tunnel</li><li>In perilunate dislocation the lunate remains in position whilst the rest of the carpus dislocates around it (worse outcomes typically than lunate dislocation)</li></ul><br /><b>Lunate dislocation associated injuries</b><br /><ul><li>Acute carpal tunnel syndrome (median nerve)</li><li>Note that for the lunate to dislocate requires disruption to all of the perilunate ligaments/articulations i.e. scapholunate ligament, capitolunate articulation, lunotriquetral articulation and dorsal radiocarpal ligament</li><li>Perilunate dislocation is the most severe form (grade IV) of perilunate instability </li></ul><br /><b>Management</b><br /><ul><li>Surgical ORIF</li><li>Very poor outcomes with non surgical management</li></ul><br /><b>Anatomy</b><br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti073b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti073.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Illustration of normal bony alignment at the wrist and carpus</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti072b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti072.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Illustration of bony alignment at the wrist and carpus in lunate and perilunate dislocation</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti069b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti069.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Lateral XRAY showing normal bony alignment at the wrist and carpus</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti070b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti070.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Lateral XRAY showing lunate dislocation volarly</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti071b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti071.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>The 'spilled teacup' sign seen on XRAY with lunate dislocation</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti074b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti074.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Normal XRAY on the left side. On the right you can see the 'piece of pie' sign seen in lunate dislocation where the lunate and capitate overlap</div></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodylinks\"><table style='width:100%'><tr><td>Wikipedia</td><td style = \"float: right;width:115px;\"><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_like_62\" data-linkid=\"62\" data-rating=\"1\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-up\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-up\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_good_count_62\" class = \"link_good_count\" style=\"color:green; font-size:85%;\">0</span><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_dislike_62\" data-linkid=\"62\" data-rating=\"0\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-down\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-down\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_bad_count_62\" class = \"link_bad_count\" style=\"color:red; font-size:85%;\">0</span></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\"><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mayfield_classification\">Mayfield classification carpal instability</a></td></tr></table></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodymedia\"></div>\n\n\n<div id=\"categorynum\">1</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategorynum\">6</div>\n\n<div id=\"categoryname\">Anatomy</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategoryname\">Upper limb anatomy</div>\n<div id=\"mybody\">\n\n<div id=\"body_content\">\n<b>Mechanism of injury</b><br /><ul><li>High energy injury </li><li>Forceful loading of dorsiflexed/extended wrist. </li><li>Uncommon injury</li><li>Potential poor outcomes</li></ul><br /><b>Lunate and perilunate dislocation</b><br /><ul><li>In lunate dislocation the lunate displaces volarly into carpal tunnel</li><li>In perilunate dislocation the lunate remains in position whilst the rest of the carpus dislocates around it (worse outcomes typically than lunate dislocation)</li></ul><br /><b>Lunate dislocation associated injuries</b><br /><ul><li>Acute carpal tunnel syndrome (median nerve)</li><li>Note that for the lunate to dislocate requires disruption to all of the perilunate ligaments/articulations i.e. scapholunate ligament, capitolunate articulation, lunotriquetral articulation and dorsal radiocarpal ligament</li><li>Perilunate dislocation is the most severe form (grade IV) of perilunate instability </li></ul><br /><b>Management</b><br /><ul><li>Surgical ORIF</li><li>Very poor outcomes with non surgical management</li></ul><br /><b>Anatomy</b><br /><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti073b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti073.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Illustration of normal bony alignment at the wrist and carpus</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti072b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti072.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Illustration of bony alignment at the wrist and carpus in lunate and perilunate dislocation</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti069b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti069.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Lateral XRAY showing normal bony alignment at the wrist and carpus</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti070b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti070.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Lateral XRAY showing lunate dislocation volarly</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti071b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti071.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>The 'spilled teacup' sign seen on XRAY with lunate dislocation</div><br /><CENTER><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti074b.png'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_FRCEMtutor/fti074.png'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'></td><td align='right'></td></tr></table></CENTER><div class='imagetext'>Normal XRAY on the left side. On the right you can see the 'piece of pie' sign seen in lunate dislocation where the lunate and capitate overlap</div></div>\n\n\n<BR><BR><table style='width:100%'><tr><td>Wikipedia</td><td style = \"float: right;width:115px;\"><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_like_62\" data-linkid=\"62\" data-rating=\"1\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-up\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-up\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_good_count_62\" class = \"link_good_count\" style=\"color:green; font-size:85%;\">0</span><button type=\"button\" style=\"\" id=\"link_dislike_62\" data-linkid=\"62\" data-rating=\"0\" class=\"rate-link btn btn-link\"><svg class=\"bi bi-hand-thumbs-down\" width=\"16\" height=\"16\"><use xlink:href=\"#icon-hand-thumbs-down\"/></svg></button><span id=\"link_bad_count_62\" class = \"link_bad_count\" style=\"color:red; font-size:85%;\">0</span><